{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507958"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:00:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:00:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2698"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2698"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.78,0.13,0.01,0.03,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2698"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79163"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2698","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2698"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2698"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64515"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"582"},{"type":"tags","id":"1137"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3323"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3357"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26824"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79163"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with haematemesis. He is resuscitated and becomes stable. He reports he has never had this occur before. He reports no medical conditions and does not take any regular medications. He describes his abdomen feeling bloated and sore, with a reduced appetite over the last few weeks and thinks he has lost some weight. He has also noted some strange \u0022skin spots\u0022 across his chest that have developed over the past few months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination he has a blood pressure of 110/70mmHg, pulse rate of 78/min, respiratory rate of 17/min, SpO2 97% on room air and temperature of 37\u00b0C. There are eight vascular lesions noted across his chest, that are small, red and blanch with pressure. He has lower limb pitting peripheral oedema to mid-shins. His abdomen is distended, tense and shifting dullness is present. He is determined to have large volume ascites and an ascitic drain is done, showing a SAAG (serum ascites albumin gradient) score of 13g/L.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of his ascites?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Portal hypertension","Malignancy","Cardiac failure","Pancreatic ascites","Protein-losing enteropathy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAscites is the pathological accumulation of fluid within the peritoneum/abdominal cavity. The SAAG (serum-ascites albumin gradient) score is the difference between the albumin content in the ascitic fluid and the albumin content in the serum. The calculation is as follows: (albumin concentration in serum) \u2013 (albumin concentration in ascitic fluid). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA gradient \u003E11g/L suggests that the ascitic fluid is transudative, most commonly secondary to portal hypertension (with 97% accuracy). Hence, it can be a helpful way of confirming \u003Cstrong\u003Eportal hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E, but importantly the cause of portal hypertension needs to be determined, with the most common cause being liver cirrhosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA low SAAG score \u003C11g/L suggests the fluid is exudative (more albumin in the ascitic fluid than in the serum). This is suggestive of an inflammatory, infective or malignant cause. These include \u003Cstrong\u003Emalignancy\u003C/strong\u003E and the other options listed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac failure\u003C/strong\u003E can cause ascites through increased right heart pressures leading to hepatic congestion. While this would also produce a high SAAG score, the presence of spider naevi and haematemesis strongly suggests portal hypertension from liver disease rather than cardiac causes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic ascites\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when there is disruption of the pancreatic duct leading to leakage of pancreatic enzymes into the peritoneal cavity. This produces a protein-rich exudative ascites with a low SAAG score and very high amylase levels in the ascitic fluid.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtein-losing enteropathy\u003C/strong\u003E can cause ascites through hypoproteinaemia, but this would typically present with a low SAAG score. Common causes include inflammatory bowel disease, intestinal lymphangiectasia, and certain infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A high SAAG score suggests the ascites is due to portal hypertension with 97% accuracy","A SAAG score \u003E11g/L suggests a transudative cause of ascites and a SAAG score \u003C11g/L suggests an exudative cause of ascites"],"references":["Younas M, Sattar A, Hashim R, Ijaz A, Dilawar M, et al. Role of serum-ascites albumin gradient in differential diagnosis of ascites. J Ayub Med Coll Abbottabad. 2012;24(3-4):97-9. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24669623/","Saif MW, Siddiqui IA, Sohail MA. Management of ascites due to gastrointestinal malignancy. Ann Saudi Med. 2009;29(5):369-377. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3290049/","Herv\u00e9 F, H\u00e9ron F, Levesque H, Marie I. Ascites as the first manifestation of polyarteritis nodosa. Scand J Gastroenterol. 2006;41(4):493-5. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16635920/#:~:text=As%20ascites%20may%20precede%20other,e.g.%20fever%2C%20weight%20loss).","Nickson C. Ascitic Fluid. In: Life in the Fast Lane [Online]. 2020. Access at: https://litfl.com/ascitic-fluid/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64515"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2698"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64515"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T15:53:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T15:55:17+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2698"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79163"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","positio